   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "06bb7292",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Reinforcement Learning - Minimalistic Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine a casino with some classic slot machines (one-arm bandits) - you can consider them as classic Laplacian probability devices: The will produce a random output, but they may have different mean values (at least for the sake of this exercise - see ``true means``: one of them will deliver the highest mean and therefore best result, ergo the highest reward).  These machines would be the **environment**.\n",
    "\n",
    "A **model/agent** is now set to do pulls at the machines. The **actions** in this case would be the different machines which can be used by the agent.\n",
    "\n",
    "In order to train a model to learn from **accumulated experience**, a **reward** is given based on the mean of the machine used. This way, the probability of using the best machine will be improving over the training epochs. The algorithm learns only from interaction — no labels, no model of the world. The true means are unknown to the agent, so the pulls will be random at first but gradually improve as the probability is adapted due to the reward.\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that in this case, the reward is immediate and the state of the environment is not changed (Laplacian probability!). Therefore, the state and future rewards (discounts) do not have to be considered here.\n",
    "\n",
    "Find below the code for this reduced example and see how you could implement RL in Pytorch."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e1b5c35a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "1) Import dependencies"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "b32dea46",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import torch\n",
    "import torch.nn as nn\n",
    "import torch.optim as optim\n",
    "from torch.distributions import Categorical # this is what actually makes this a policy gradient, instead of classic supervised learning\n",
    "import numpy as np"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6c5532ab",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "2. Define the environment\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that on the reward, some Gaussian noise is added to capture variance and uncertainty. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "cbddaa08",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Bandit environment: The basic description of a random machine with a certain mean\n",
    "class Bandit:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, means):\n",
    "        self.means = means\n",
    "\n",
    "    def pull(self, action):\n",
    "        # Gaussian reward from pulling a chosen arm \n",
    "        return np.random.randn() + self.means[action]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0d9deacc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "3) Define the policy\n",
    "\n",
    "Policy = how the agent decides on an action. In this case, only an array of trainable numbers for each action. No network, no states -> simplest possible policy.\n",
    "\n",
    "These trainable numbers will be converted to actual probabilities using the softmax function (ensures that all probabilities are >= 0 and the total sum is 1). This makes the gradient well-behaved."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "e40ef67b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "# Policy\n",
    "class Policy(nn.Module):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, num_arms):\n",
    "        super().__init__()\n",
    "        # One learnable logit per arm\n",
    "        self.logits = nn.Parameter(torch.zeros(num_arms))\n",
    "\n",
    "    def forward(self):\n",
    "        return torch.softmax(self.logits, dim=0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e25c87e5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "4) Setup\n",
    "\n",
    "The number of slot machines and which one is the best. The agent does not know the latter!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "6714453c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Setup\n",
    "num_arms = 5\n",
    "true_means = [0.2, 1.0, -0.3, 0.5, 0.0]  # second arm (index = 1) is best\n",
    "env = Bandit(true_means)\n",
    "\n",
    "policy = Policy(num_arms)\n",
    "optimizer = optim.Adam(policy.parameters(), lr=0.1)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define baseline (variance reduction) - very important!\n",
    "# Basically helps to determine: \"Was this reward better than usual?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "baseline = 0.0\n",
    "alpha = 0.9  # baseline smoothing\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "31723378",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "5) Training\n",
    "\n",
    "Note: \n",
    "- Sampling is used instead of argmax - this means that the agent needs to explore instead of just going for the max (exploit).\n",
    "\n",
    "- The probability loss will be updated based on the ``advantage`` (better or worse than baseline), not the reward directly!\n",
    "\n",
    "- ``log_prob(action)`` measures how likely the policy made this action. We want to maximise the reward, hence the negative sign, as pytorch normally wants to minimise loss! (bigger reward -> higher probability -> lower loss)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "dad952b6",
   "metadata": {},
